ile_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/device-auth-login/review-01.md\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":132,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":19953,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":132,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":25,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ2mgtBXMUCfqb9q6xrdS\",\"uuid\":\"aafa2b53-d1f1-4e6d-b27b-e1122555dd00\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a713062a872c2d8d3\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NTuMV5ZbpfAYdR7H5mQQ8y\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01H6xkMdUbRJbb54L58NNMnv\",\"uuid\":\"1d3be027-2311-43c7-94a4-b701a9087dce\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:55:19.589Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1d3be027-2311-43c7-94a4-b701a9087dce\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_015zK2XSirK74899LLrg6QFR\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Review 01\\n     2→\\n     3→> Status: pending-dev\\n     4→> Date: 2026-03-14\\n     5→> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n     6→> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n     7→\\n     8→## Previous Review Status\\n     9→\\n    10→No previous reviews.\\n    11→\\n    12→## New Findings\\n    13→\\n    14→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    15→\\n    16→1. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:47] Missing HTTP client timeout**\\n    17→\\n    18→   `NewClient(nil)` creates an `&http.Client{}` with zero timeout. This means every HTTP request (both `StartDeviceAuth` and `PollDeviceAuth`) will block indefinitely if the server accepts the TCP connection but never responds. While the context passed to individual requests provides cancellation, the default `http.Client` does not enforce a connection or TLS handshake timeout.\\n    19→\\n    20→   Suggested fix: Set a reasonable overall timeout on the default client:\\n    21→   ```go\\n    22→   httpClient = &http.Client{Timeout: 30 * time.Second}\\n    23→   ```\\n    24→\\n    25→   Note: The existing `versioncheck` package has the same pattern (`&http.Client{}`), but that code runs with a 2-second context timeout. The login poll loop has no such outer timeout guard per-request -- it only checks the expiry deadline _between_ polls.\\n    26→\\n    27→2. **[cmd/entire/cli/api/base_url_test.go] Missing `t.Parallel()` on tests that use `t.Setenv()`**\\n    28→\\n    29→   `TestBaseURL_Default`, `TestBaseURL_Override`, and `TestResolveURL` all call `t.Setenv()` which mutates process-global state. Per the CLAUDE.md guidelines, `t.Setenv()` and `t.Parallel()` cannot be combined (Go panics). However, these tests also do NOT call `t.Parallel()`, which is inconsistent with the project convention that says \\\"Always use `t.Parallel()` in tests\\\" with the exception being tests that modify process-global state. The current code is technically correct (since `t.Setenv` is process-global), but should have a comment explaining why `t.Parallel()` is omitted, per convention:\\n    30→   ```go\\n    31→   // No t.Parallel() -- t.Setenv mutates process-global state.\\n    32→   ```\\n    33→\\n    34→   Similarly, `TestLookupToken` in `store_test.go` uses `t.Setenv()` without `t.Parallel()` and should have the same comment.\\n    35→\\n    36→### Important (Should Fix)\\n    37→\\n    38→3. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:108-128] `waitForApproval` poll logic has a subtle flow issue with `authorization_pending`**\\n    39→\\n    40→   When `result.Error == \\\"\\\"` (success) AND `result.AccessToken != \\\"\\\"`, the function correctly returns the token on line 128. However, when `result.Error == \\\"authorization_pending\\\"`, the switch falls through to \\\"continue below\\\" (line 109), but then the `if result.Error == \\\"\\\"` check on line 124 is false, so it falls through to the `select` sleep -- which is correct. But the empty-string case in the switch (line 109) ALSO falls through to sleep, which is the success path. This means if the server returns `200 OK` with `{\\\"access_token\\\": \\\"tok\\\"}` (Error is `\\\"\\\"`), the switch case `\\\"\\\"` matches, executes \\\"continue below\\\", then `result.Error == \\\"\\\"` on line 124 triggers and returns the token. This works, but the control flow is needlessly confusing because the `\\\"\\\"` case serves double duty (success + pending-but-no-error). A clearer structure would be:\\n    41→\\n    42→   ```go\\n    43→   switch result.Error {\\n    44→   case \\\"\\\":\\n    45→       if result.AccessToken == \\\"\\\" {\\n    46→           return \\\"\\\", errors.New(\\\"device authorization completed without a token\\\")\\n    47→       }\\n    48→       return result.AccessToken, nil\\n    49→   case \\\"authorization_pending\\\":\\n    50→       // continue to sleep\\n    51→   case \\\"slow_down\\\":\\n    52→       // ...\\n    53→   ```\\n    54→\\n    55→   This makes the success exit explicit in the switch and removes the second `if result.Error == \\\"\\\"` check entirely.\\n    56→\\n    57→4. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:87-96] Poll interval does not cap to `maxPollInterval` on initial value**\\n    58→\\n    59→   The `pollInterval` is set from the server's `interval` field. If the server returns `interval: 60` (or some large value), `pollInterval` would be 60 seconds with no cap applied. Only the `slow_down` case applies the `maxPollInterval` cap. The initial value should also be capped:\\n    60→   ```go\\n    61→   if pollInterval <= 0 {\\n    62→       pollInterval = fallbackDeviceAuthPollInterval\\n    63→   }\\n    64→   if pollInterval > maxPollInterval {\\n    65→       pollInterval = maxPollInterval\\n    66→   }\\n    67→   ```\\n    68→\\n    69→5. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:139-172] `openBrowser` on Windows may have URL argument injection**\\n    70→\\n    71→   On Windows, the command is `cmd /c start \\\"\\\" <url>`. The `url.Parse` check on line 141 validates the scheme is `http` or `https`, which prevents `file://` and other schemes. However, a malicious server could return a `verification_uri_complete` containing shell metacharacters (e.g., `https://evil.com/x&calc`). On Windows, `cmd /c start \\\"\\\" \\\"https://evil.com/x&calc\\\"` could execute `calc` because `&` is a command separator for `cmd.exe`.\\n    72→\\n    73→   The URL is already parsed by `url.Parse` which would URL-encode special characters in the path, but the _original string_ `browserURL` is passed to `cmd`, not the re-serialized URL. If the server returns a URL with literal `&` in it (which is valid in query strings), this could be exploited.\\n    74→\\n    75→   Suggested fix: On Windows, use `url.String()` (the re-serialized, properly escaped form) instead of the raw string:\\n    76→   ```go\\n    77→   case \\\"windows\\\":\\n    78→       command = \\\"cmd\\\"\\n    79→       args = []string{\\\"/c\\\", \\\"start\\\", \\\"\\\", u.String()}\\n    80→   ```\\n    81→   Or better yet, use `rundll32 url.dll,FileProtocolHandler` which doesn't go through `cmd.exe` shell parsing.\\n    82→\\n    83→6. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/store.go:46-61] `SaveToken` has a TOCTOU race on concurrent calls**\\n    84→\\n    85→   If two processes call `SaveToken` simultaneously (e.g., user runs `entire login` twice in different terminals pointing to different base URLs), both will `Load()` the current state, then each will write their own version. The second write wins and the first token is lost. The atomic rename prevents corruption, but not data loss.\\n    86→\\n    87→   This is a low-probability scenario for a CLI tool, but worth noting. A file lock (e.g., `flock`) would prevent it. At minimum, add a comment acknowledging the limitation.\\n    88→\\n    89→7. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/store.go:81-87] Hardcoded `~/.config/entire/` path ignores `XDG_CONFIG_HOME`**\\n    90→\\n    91→   On Linux, the XDG Base Directory Specification says config files should go in `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME` (defaulting to `~/.config`). The current code hardcodes `~/.config/entire`. While `versioncheck` does the same thing, this is a good opportunity to respect `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` since this is new code:\\n    92→   ```go\\n    93→   func defaultFilePath() (string, error) {\\n    94→       configDir := os.Getenv(\\\"XDG_CONFIG_HOME\\\")\\n    95→       if configDir == \\\"\\\" {\\n    96→           home, err := os.UserHomeDir()\\n    97→           if err != nil {\\n    98→               return \\\"\\\", fmt.Errorf(\\\"get home directory: %w\\\", err)\\n    99→           }\\n   100→           configDir = filepath.Join(home, \\\".config\\\")\\n   101→       }\\n   102→       return filepath.Join(configDir, \\\"entire\\\", authFileName), nil\\n   103→   }\\n   104→   ```\\n   105→\\n   106→   Alternatively, use `os.UserConfigDir()` which handles this cross-platform. However, since `versioncheck` also hardcodes `~/.config`, this could be deferred to a follow-up that fixes both.\\n   107→\\n   108→8. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:22] Package-level `var browserOpener` is a testing seam that is never overridden in tests**\\n   109→\\n   110→   The `browserOpener` variable exists to allow test injection, but no test actually overrides it. The integration tests use `--print-browser-url` to skip browser opening entirely. This is fine for now, but the variable is exported-ish (package-level) mutation surface. If tests don't need it, consider removing it and calling `openBrowser` directly. If tests will need it in the future, add a `// browserOpener is a testing seam for openBrowser.` comment.\\n   111→\\n   112→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n   113→\\n   114→9. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:23-29] Consider using `decodeJSON` (lenient) for `StartDeviceAuth` instead of `decodeJSONStrict`**\\n   115→\\n   116→   The start response uses `decodeJSONStrict` which rejects unknown fields. This means if the server adds a new field (e.g., `message` for user display), older CLI versions will break. The poll response already uses lenient decoding. For forward compatibility, consider using lenient decoding for both, or at least document why strict is intentional for the start response.\\n   117→\\n   118→   The current strict decode acts as a contract validator -- if the server sends unexpected fields, the CLI fails fast. This is a defensible choice, but it trades resilience for strictness. RFC 8628 Section 3.2 says the response \\\"includes\\\" certain fields but does not say \\\"only\\\" those fields.\\n   119→\\n   120→10. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:87] Consider using `time.NewTimer` instead of `time.After` in the poll loop**\\n   121→\\n   122→    `time.After` creates a new channel/timer each iteration, and unused timers are not garbage collected until they fire. For a poll loop that could run for up to 15 minutes with 1-second intervals, this creates ~900 leaked timers. Using `time.NewTimer` with `Reset()` avoids this:\\n   123→    ```go\\n   124→    timer := time.NewTimer(pollInterval)\\n   125→    defer timer.Stop()\\n   126→    for {\\n   127→        // ...\\n   128→        timer.Reset(pollInterval)\\n   129→        select {\\n   130→        case <-ctx.Done():\\n   131→            return \\\"\\\", fmt.Errorf(\\\"wait for approval: %w\\\", ctx.Err())\\n   132→        case <-timer.C:\\n   133→        }\\n   134→    }\\n   135→    ```\\n   136→\\n   137→11. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:174-188] `decodeJSONWithOptions` reads the entire body into memory then creates a decoder**\\n   138→\\n   139→    The function calls `io.ReadAll(io.LimitReader(r, maxResponseBytes))` to read the body into `[]byte`, then wraps it in `bytes.NewReader` for the JSON decoder. This double-buffers the response. Since the response is already limited to 1MB this is not a real concern, but a simpler approach would be to use `json.NewDecoder(io.LimitReader(r, maxResponseBytes))` directly:\\n   140→    ```go\\n   141→    dec := json.NewDecoder(io.LimitReader(r, maxResponseBytes))\\n   142→    ```\\n   143→    The current approach may have been chosen to get the full body for error reporting, but no error context is added.\\n   144→\\n   145→12. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:40] Consider checking if user is already logged in**\\n   146→\\n   147→    The command does not check if a valid token already exists before starting the device auth flow. A small UX improvement would be to check `LookupToken` first and either skip the flow or prompt the user:\\n   148→    ```\\n   149→    You are already logged in to https://entire.io. Run again to re-authenticate.\\n   150→    ```\\n   151→\\n   152→13. **[scripts/local-device-auth-smoke.sh] The smoke script depends on `python3` being installed**\\n   153→\\n   154→    The script uses `python3` for parsing the log file output. `grep` + `sed` or `awk` could accomplish the same thing without the dependency:\\n   155→    ```bash\\n   156→    APPROVAL_URL=\\\"$(grep '^Approval URL: ' \\\"${LOG_FILE}\\\" | sed 's/^Approval URL: //')\\\"\\n   157→    ```\\n   158→\\n   159→14. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:98-101] The client-side expiry check races with the server**\\n   160→\\n   161→    The `waitForApproval` function checks `time.Now().After(deadline)` at the top of each loop iteration. If the client's clock and server's clock are slightly out of sync, the client could time out before the server considers the code expired (or vice versa). This is inherent to the device auth flow and fine in practice, but worth noting that the `expired_token` server response (line 118-119) is the authoritative check and the client-side deadline is just a safety net.\\n   162→\\n   163→### Praise\\n   164→\\n   165→- **Token storage security is solid.** The atomic temp-file-rename pattern with `0o600` permissions and `0o700` directory permissions is the right approach. The `fsync` before rename ensures durability.\\n   166→\\n   167→- **Good forward-compatibility in the auth file format.** Using lenient JSON unmarshaling for `Load()` (via standard `json.Unmarshal` which ignores unknown fields) and the `TestStoreLoad_IgnoresUnknownFields` test explicitly verifies this.\\n   168→\\n   169→- **Well-structured integration tests.** The `loginProcess` abstraction with background process management, `waitForLoginPrompt` with deadline, and the mock HTTP server with mutex-protected state is clean and follows existing integration test patterns.\\n   170→\\n   171→- **Proper RFC 8628 compliance.** The `slow_down` backoff handling, `authorization_pending` polling, `expired_token` and `access_denied` terminal states, and the correct grant type URN (`urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:device_code`) all match the spec.\\n   172→\\n   173→- **Good separation of concerns.** The `apiurl`, `auth` (client + store), and `login` command packages are well-factored. The `apiurl` package is reusable for future API calls. The `Client` captures the base URL at construction time, preventing mid-flow URL changes.\\n   174→\\n   175→- **URL scheme validation in `openBrowser`.** Checking for `http`/`https` only before passing to OS commands is the right defense against `file://`, `javascript:`, or other scheme-based attacks.\\n   176→\\n   177→- **The `--print-browser-url` flag.** This is thoughtful for headless environments, CI, and the accessibility story. It also makes the integration tests simpler and more reliable by avoiding browser launch.\\n   178→\\n   179→## Summary\\n   180→\\n   181→- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n   182→- **Key concerns:**\\n   183→  - The missing HTTP client timeout (item 1) is the most impactful issue -- a hung server connection could block the CLI indefinitely.\\n   184→  - The Windows command injection vector in `openBrowser` (item 5) is a security concern that should be addressed before merge.\\n   185→  - The confusing control flow in `waitForApproval` (item 3) is a readability issue that could lead to bugs in future maintenance.\\n   186→- **Estimated effort:** 1-2 hours to address Critical and Important items. The code is well-written overall and the issues are mostly small targeted fixes.\\n   187→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"917ae5ec-37ef-4030-ad5f-13bad7efcdcb\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:55:19.613Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a713062a872c2d8d3\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NTuMV5ZbpfAYdR7H5mQQ8y\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01H6xkMdUbRJbb54L58NNMnv\",\"uuid\":\"d590265c-d4cc-4b56-a43c-f6b6c8ab9ea7\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:55:19.614Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"d590265c-d4cc-4b56-a43c-f6b6c8ab9ea7\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:55:24.283Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Be9C9yi1nGMtkxJUUzEyRG\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01NYkHGA6D4q7V6bJMMv28uC\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/api/base_url.go\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4425,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":19953,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":4425,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ2mh8JL